<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870429-0190 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:Unhappy Returns</HL><DD> 04/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   I am the wife, sister and cousin of Vietnam veterans. I cannot believe the ignorance of your reader (Letters, April 2) who asked why Vietnam veterans can't just get on with their lives, as WWII veterans have done.    WWII veterans seem to live in past glory, while Vietnam veterans live with past, present and future silent agonies. One can hardly compare the very popular and patriotic &quot;Big One&quot; to the Vietnam conflict. Returning WWII veterans were treated as heroes. Does your reader recall how returning Vietnam veterans were treated? Also, does he remember how many glamorous movies were quickly made about WWII? It took more than 20 years before a seemingly accurate portrayal about Vietnam could be produced. Doesn't that say it all?    Pauline F. Fuller   Lake Geneva, Wis.</TEXT></DOC>